Note that we are in Python¶

Working directory must contain subdirectories,supp_data¶

supp_data/ should contain the file:¶

SCT_dge_50k.txt (get it by using the same method as in notebook 4-1)
geometry.txt (extract it from geometry_arabidopsis_root_binarized.txt by keeping only the geometry part)
49_marker_binarized_dge.txt

def makeColours( vals ):
    colours = np.zeros( (len(vals),3) )
    norm = Normalize( vmin=vals.min(), vmax=vals.max() )

    #Can put any colormap you like here.
    colours = [cm.ScalarMappable( norm=norm, cmap='viridis_r').to_rgba( val ) for val in vals]

    return colours

def seplt(gid):
    plt.figure(figsize=(32,2))
    plt.scatter(locations[:, 2], locations[:, 0], c=sdge[np.argwhere(gene_names == gid)[0], :].flatten(), s=50)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
    plt.scatter(locations[:, 0], locations[:, 1], c=sdge[np.argwhere(gene_names == gid)[0], :].flatten(), s=50)
    plt.axis('off')
In [4]:
def sseplt(gid):
    densObj = kde(sdge[np.argwhere(gene_names == gid)[0], :].flatten())
    colours = makeColours(densObj.evaluate(sdge[np.argwhere(gene_names == gid)[0], :].flatten()) )
    plt.figure(figsize=(32,2))
    plt.scatter(locations[:, 2], locations[:, 0], c=colours, s=50)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
    plt.scatter(locations[:, 0], locations[:, 1], c=colours, s=50)
    plt.axis('off')

Import data¶

Import the gene names and the gene expression matrix. Although novoSpaRc can also operate on raw data, it performs much better when the gene expression matrix is already normalized. Note the format: cells in rows and genes in columns.

In [5]:
# Import SCTransformed expression matrix with a subset of randomly selected 50 k cells
dge_path = './supp_data/SCT_dge_50k.txt'
gene_names = np.genfromtxt(dge_path, skip_header=True, dtype='str', usecols=range(1))
dge = np.genfromtxt(dge_path, skip_header=True, usecols=range(1, 50001))
dge = dge.T
num_cells = dge.shape[0]

Create the target space¶

Creating the target space that represents the biological tissue plays an important role, as it influences the geometric component of the reconstruction. In the case where the physical cellular locations are known, such as in the case of the early Drosophila embryo, it is better to use these:

In [8]:

Reconstruct the tissue by using reference marker genes¶

Available reference marker genes assist novoSpaRc and result in general in a much better reconstruction. The setup of the reconstruction is the same as before. Here we only need to compute the cost matrix for the reference marker genes. First, import the reference database.

In [12]:
geometry_path = './supp_data/geometry.txt'
locations = np.loadtxt(geometry_path, skiprows=1)
# keep all x, y, z coordination
locations = locations[:, [0,1,2]]
# use all 3957 locations from the geometry
locations = locations[:3957, :]
num_locations = locations.shape[0]

cost_expression, cost_locations = nc.rc.setup_for_OT_reconstruction(dge_hvg,
                                                                    locations,
                                                                    num_neighbors_source = 5,
                                                                    num_neighbors_target = 5)
p_locations, p_expression = nc.rc.create_space_distributions(num_locations, num_cells)

# The file contains spatial expression of all markers
bdtnp_path = './supp_data/49_marker_binarized_dge.txt'

Leave-one-out cross validation¶

In [23]:
pc_list = {}
for j in range(100):
    # hold out 1 for test
    train_id = random.sample(range(0, 49), 48)
    test_id = np.delete(np.array(range(0,49)), train_id)
    insitu_genes = np.genfromtxt(bdtnp_path, usecols= train_id, dtype='str', max_rows=1)
    insitu_matrix = np.loadtxt(bdtnp_path, usecols=train_id, skiprows=1)
    test_genes = np.genfromtxt(bdtnp_path, usecols= test_id, dtype='str', max_rows=1)
    test_matrix = np.loadtxt(bdtnp_path, usecols=test_id, skiprows=1)
    markers_in_sc = np.array([], dtype='int')
    for marker in insitu_genes:
        marker_index = np.where(gene_names == marker)[0]
        if len(marker_index) > 0:
            markers_in_sc = np.append(markers_in_sc, marker_index[0])
    cost_marker_genes = cdist(dge[:, markers_in_sc]/np.amax(dge[:, markers_in_sc]),
                          insitu_matrix/np.amax(insitu_matrix))
    alpha_linear = 0.5
    gw = nc.rc._GWadjusted.gromov_wasserstein_adjusted_norm(cost_marker_genes, cost_expression, cost_locations,
                                                            alpha_linear, p_expression, p_locations,
                                                            'square_loss', epsilon=5e-3, verbose=True)
    sdge = np.dot(dge.T, gw)
    pc = np.array([])
    
    predict = sdge[np.argwhere(gene_names == test_genes)[0][0], :].flatten()
    truth = test_matrix[:,]
    corr, _ = pearsonr(predict, truth)
    pc = np.append(pc, corr)
        
    pc_list['Iteration_{}'.format(j)] = pc[0]
